1. What happens when you initialize a repository? Why do you need to do it?
When you initiate a repository, a hidden git directory is created, but no commit is made. You need to do it to start using Git Bash do the version control of your files.

2.How is the staging area different from the working directory and the repository? What value do you think it offers?
The staging area is differnt because it only contains the files you've explicitly added to it. It's valuable because it allows you to chose what you want to be part of each of your commits.

3. How can you use the staging area to make sure you have one commit per logical change?
You can choose what files to put in the staging area, and only those will be changed when you make the new commit.

4. What are some situations when branches would be helpful in keeping your history organized? How would branches help?
Branches are useful when you want to make an alternative version of your project, but continuing working on the other version.

5.How do the diagrams help you visualize the branch structure?
They help a lot, especially with branches.

7. What is the result of merging two branches together? Why do we represent it in the diagram the way we do?
Merge two branches will create a new commit, with the changes made by in the two branches. The diagram is used to make it easier to visualize what Git Bash is doing.

8. What are the pros and cons of Gitâ€™s automatic merging vs. always doing merges manually?
Automaticv merging is fster and requires less works, but it doesn't always work. Furthermore, when manualy merging you know exactly how your code is being modified.